  ### 1. Distinguishing Multiple Database Clients via Attributes (Dimensions)

  In OTel, you do not differentiate between distinct database technologies by changing the metric name (e.g., avoiding  oxia.client.op.duration  vs
  postgres.client.op.duration ). Instead, all databases write to the same metric  db.client.operation.duration , and they are distinguished using standardized attributes:

  •  db.system : Identifies the database system. For this library, the value is statically set to  "oxia" . For PostgreSQL, it would be  "postgresql" . For etcd,  "etcd" .
  •  db.name : Identifies the specific database instance, cluster, or namespace (e.g.,  "metadata-namespace" ).
  •  server.address  /  server.port : Differentiates between physical server endpoints.

  This allows operations teams to create a unified database health dashboard showing total database query latencies across the entire application stack, with the ability to
  filter or group by  db.system .
  ──────
  ### 2. Nested Database Clients (Oxia as a Coordinator/Metadata Store)

  If your application is a database system itself (e.g., a custom distributed storage engine) that uses Oxia internally for coordination:

  1. Outer Client Spans/Metrics: The parent database client emits metrics with  db.client.operation.duration  where  db.system = "your_custom_db" .
  2. Inner Coordinator Spans/Metrics: The nested Oxia Rust client emits metrics with  db.client.operation.duration  where  db.system = "oxia" .

  This separation allows operators to:

  • View total user-facing latency ( db.system = "your_custom_db" ).
  • Correlate user queries with internal coordination overhead by filtering on  db.system = "oxia"  to see how much of the latency budget was consumed by metadata lookups.
  ──────
  ### Proposing Updates to the Design Document

  I will update Section 9 (Semantic Conventions and Cross-Language Consistency) of the design documents to explicitly clarify this behavior and design rationale for future
  implementers and reviewers.

